Wings Over Arkansas Award Program This Booklet Belongs To Name: _______________________________________________ Address: ______________________________________________ City, State, Zip__________________________________________ INTRODUCTION The Arkansas Bird CheckList Booklet is a part of the Arkansas Game 
It is designed to enhance the user's opportunity to view, record and understand Arkansas's wide diversity of bird life.
Our hope is the checklist will help the user become more familiar with the birds in Arkansas and provide an organized manner to record individual sightings.
Arkansas contains a diversity of natural areas, offering excellent birding opportunities.
Upland forests of hardwood and pine offer habitat for woodland birds, while the delta farms and prairies provide abundant food for the open country birds.
Rice fields, flooded timber and the many waterways in the state are home to resident waterfowl, as well as an excellent stop over for migrating waterfowl.
Neotropical migrant birds using the Mississippi Flyway refuel in Arkansas on their annual spring and fall migrations.
Backyards have become an important resource for birdwatching.
Providing birdfeeders, a water source and landscaping for wildlife creates excellent viewing opportunities for most homes.
PLACES TO GO: Arkansas Game and Fish Commission Wildlife Management Areas Arkansas Game and Fish Hatcheries Arkansas Game and Fish Lakes Arkansas State Parks National Parks National Wildlife Refuges National Forests U.S. Army Corps of Engineers Lakes An Arkansas state highway map is a good way to locate the above areas or you can call individual agencies for more information.
Joining a local birding club is a great way to learn and meet people of the same interest.
Some of the organizations of interest are: National Audubon Society 950 Third Avenue New York, NY 10022 Audubon Society of North Central Arkansas 913 Arbor Street Mountain Home, Arkansas 72653
Other books of interest are: "Arkansas Birds, Their Distribution and Abundance" , Douglas A. James 
Optics are available in many different price ranges.
It is advisable to purchase the best equipment your budget will allow.
The "7x35" or "8x40" power binocular is recommended for the beginning birder.
If you wear glasses, make sure the rubber cups on the eyepieces fold back to enable you to wear your glasses while using the binocular.
A light weight binocular is more comfortable for long periods of time in the field.
Since a good quality spotting scope is very expensive, it is recommended for the more advanced birder.
Consult optic catalogs and visit stores to try out any optics before buying.
BIRDING ETHICS
Arkansas Audubon Society 2426 South Main Street Malvern, Arkansas 72104 Field Guide-The use of a field guide is a necessity when trying to identify birds.
The field guide should contain a picture of the bird, a range map, and information about each species.
After you have purchased a guide, take the time to familiarize yourself with the book.
Learn arrangement of species, how they are grouped, general size, shape and appearance of families.
Learn the birds in your area.
There are several good guides listed below: "Stokes Field Guide to Birds: Eastern Eastern Birds"( Peterson Field Guides) Region" by Donald 
Ã˜ Promote the welfare of birds and their environment.
Ã˜ Stay on existing roads, trails and paths to avoid disturbing fragile habitat.
Ã˜ Observe and photograph birds without knowingly disturbing them.
Ã˜ Limit use of recording devices and other means of attracting birds.
Do not use these methods in heavily birded areas.
Ã˜ Keep well back from nests, roosts and feeding sites.
Ã˜ DO NOT handle birds or eggs.
Ã˜ Avoid flushing or chasing birds.
Leave all habitat as it was found.
Ã˜ Pick up litter Ã˜ Always get the landowner's permission before entering private property.
Ã˜ Respect the interest, rights and skills of fellow birders.
Ã˜ Observe all laws and rules which govern public use areas for birding.
Ã˜ Keep group size small so not to threaten the environment or disturb wildlife or other birders.
Ã˜ Assume responsibility for the conduct of your group.
Ã˜ Teach others good birding ethics by your example.
These ethical guidelines are provided by the American Birding Association.
